NODE.JS GUIDE

What is Node.js?

Node.js is a JavaScript runtime built on the V8 engine that allows JavaScript to run on the server.

Common Uses:
- REST APIs
- Real-time applications
- Microservices
- Background jobs

--------------------------------------------------
CREATE A BASIC SERVER
--------------------------------------------------

const http = require("http");

const server = http.createServer(
  (req, res) => {
    res.end("Hello World");
  }
);

server.listen(3000);

--------------------------------------------------
EXPRESS SETUP
--------------------------------------------------

const express = require("express");

const app = express();

app.listen(3000);

--------------------------------------------------
MIDDLEWARE
--------------------------------------------------

JSON Parser:

app.use(express.json());

Custom Middleware:

app.use((req, res, next) => {
  console.log(req.url);
  next();
});

Purpose:
- Authentication
- Logging
- Validation
- Error handling

--------------------------------------------------
ROUTES
--------------------------------------------------

GET Route:

app.get("/users", (req, res) => {
  res.json([]);
});

POST Route:

app.post("/users", (req, res) => {
  res.json(req.body);
});

PUT Route:

app.put("/users/:id", handler);

DELETE Route:

app.delete("/users/:id", handler);

--------------------------------------------------
ASYNC AWAIT
--------------------------------------------------

async function getUsers() {
  const users = await User.find();
  return users;
}

Benefits:
- Cleaner code
- Easier error handling

--------------------------------------------------
ERROR HANDLING
--------------------------------------------------

try {
  await saveUser();
} catch (error) {
  console.error(error);
}

Express Error Middleware:

app.use((err, req, res, next) => {
  res.status(500).json({
    message: err.message
  });
});

--------------------------------------------------
JWT AUTHENTICATION
--------------------------------------------------

Generate Token:

jwt.sign(
  { userId: user._id },
  SECRET_KEY,
  { expiresIn: "7d" }
);

Verify Token:

jwt.verify(
  token,
  SECRET_KEY
);

Common Flow:
1. User logs in.
2. Server generates token.
3. Client stores token.
4. Token sent in Authorization header.
5. Server verifies token.

--------------------------------------------------
FILE UPLOAD
--------------------------------------------------

Using Multer:

const upload = multer({
  dest: "uploads/"
});

app.post(
  "/upload",
  upload.single("file"),
  handler
);

--------------------------------------------------
ENVIRONMENT VARIABLES
--------------------------------------------------

.env

PORT=3000
MONGO_URI=mongodb://localhost
JWT_SECRET=secret

Access:

process.env.PORT

Benefits:
- Secure configuration
- Environment separation

--------------------------------------------------
COMMON FOLDER STRUCTURE
--------------------------------------------------

src/

controllers/
services/
repositories/
models/
routes/
middlewares/
utils/
config/

app.js

--------------------------------------------------
EVENT LOOP
--------------------------------------------------

Example:

console.log("1");

setTimeout(() => {
  console.log("2");
}, 0);

console.log("3");

Output:

1
3
2

Reason:
JavaScript executes synchronous code first, then processes callback queue tasks.

--------------------------------------------------
STREAMS
--------------------------------------------------

Readable Stream
Writable Stream
Duplex Stream
Transform Stream

Use streams for:
- Large file processing
- File uploads
- Video streaming

--------------------------------------------------
PERFORMANCE BEST PRACTICES
--------------------------------------------------

- Use async/await.
- Avoid blocking operations.
- Use database indexes.
- Implement pagination.
- Cache frequently accessed data.
- Use streams for large files.
- Optimize database queries.

